---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Dust Geometry - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Dust Geometry</h1>

    <p>
      <strong>Dust geometry</strong> describes the spatial distribution of dust relative to stars and gas within galaxies. Variations in dust geometry change the relative reddening seen by nebular emission and the stellar continuum; Karthikeyan et al. (2026) interpret changes in ΔE(B−V) with redshift as evidence for evolving dust geometry (Section IV). [Section IV]</p>
    
    <h2 id="implications">Implications</h2>
    <p>Understanding dust geometry is necessary to interpret SED-derived properties and to convert stellar E(B−V) to nebular corrections in surveys lacking Balmer decrements (Karthikeyan et al. 2026, Section III.2). [Section III.2]</p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Karthikeyan, S., Clarke, L., Shapley, A. E., et al. (2026). "Balmer Decrements and Nebular-Stellar Reddening in JADES Galaxies at 2.7&lt;z&lt;7." arXiv:2603.11338. <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11338">https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11338</a> (Sections III–IV).</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
